subSubSection.paragraph:
Head hexagonal, wider than long (HW/HL=2.32); eyes medium size and positioned posteriorly; two parallel frontal processes, shorter than scape, and basal distance between processes approximately four times basal width of each one; V-shaped frontal sulcus incomplete, curved arms not joined medially; one minor macrosetae and one major macrosetae near to edge of eye, one major macrosetae posterior to edge of eye (
Fig. 2
). Antennae almost reaching apex of abdomen, scape with three long setae at middle of dorsal face; antennomere 1 (scape) longer than wide (AW/AL=0.40), antennomere 2 (pedicel) (AW/AL=0.53) and antennomere 3(AW/AL=0.34) longer than wide, inverted piriform, with several macrosetae near apex, antennomeres 1-3 without microtrichae, antennomeres 4-11 oblong shape, the same width from the base to the apex, with microtrichae and several macrosetae, antennomere 4 (AW/AL=0.37), antennomere 5 (AW/AL=0.37), antennomere 6 (AW/AL=0.36), antennomere 7 (AW/AL=0.36), antennomeres 8 (AW/AL=0.36), antennomere 9 (AW/AL=0.39), antennomere 10 (AW/AL=0.39), antennomere 11 (AW/AL=0.27). Labrum transverse, anterior margin emarginate, six setae in the middle and each lateral third with two macrosetae apical and two macrosetae subapical (
Fig. 3
). Epipharynx with one lobe at each side, length around 2.5 times the median length of labrum. Mandibles with trifurcate apex (
Fig. 6
), dorsal teeth little shorter than ventral teeth; right mandible with small depression in dorsal tooth and with three setae, left mandible with two setae in a small depression; internal border asymmetrical, in right mandible with an area that resemble a tooth, absent in left mandible (
Fig. 6
). Maxillary palpus with palpomere 4 shorter than 2 and 3 combined (
Fig. 5
). Mentum two times wider than long and with five setae in each lateral side (
Fig. 4
). Neck narrower than head.

Pronotum wider than long (PW/PL=1.79) anterior angles projected forward; longitudinal median sulcus conspicuous; basal constriction represent one-quarter the pronotum length, with small acute projection in the basal constriction; apical three-quarters with parallel sides; slight margination anterior to each abrupt basal constriction with one setae; anterior and posterior margin with microtrichae, one setae near to anterior margin equidistant to longitudinal median sulcus and lateral margin, one setae near to anterior angle in anterior margin, three setae in the anterior angle projected, one setae in the middle lateral margin, one setae near to anterior angle, one setae in slight margination and one in the basal constriction (
Fig. 2
).

Scutellum visible, developed and triangular in shape, basal portion with fine punctures. Elytra wider than long (EL/EW =1.14). Elytrum with seven striae, sixth stria incomplete; seven setae near to lateral margin, two setae near anterior margin, one in second stria and other in fifth stria, one setae near posterior margin in fourth striae (
Fig. 2
); posterior margin emarginated. Epipleural carina present.

Abdomen. Tergites III–VII with punctures only in anterolateral regions, one pair of paratergites; tergites IV–VI with one long setae on each lateral third; sternites IV–VII with six short setae, each lateral third with 3 oblique setae, which start from inferior corner. Tergite VIII slightly curved in apical margin with ten short setae in the apical half (
Fig. 7
); sternite VIII slightly curved in apical margin with ten long setae in the apical half (
Fig. 8
); tergite IX in dorsal view divided by tergite X in two equal parts with two long setae in apical half (
Fig. 9
); tergite IX in ventral view with six setae in apical half; tergite X with two long setae and two short setae on apex (
Fig. 9
); sternite IX with two short setae in apex (
Fig. 10
). Median lobe of aedeagus curved (
Fig. 12
) with bulbous base (
Fig. 11
), parameres much longer than median lobe in lateral view (
Fig. 11
), internal sclerites as in 
Figs. 11–12
.

Female
. Similar to male, except apex of sternite VIII slightly acute, gonocoxites divided longitudinally (
Fig. 13
). The distal plates are small and slender each with a pair of microsetae; the proximal plates are bigger than distal plates with the apex acute (
Fig. 13
). Spermathecal duct around 3 times the length of spermatheca, duct sclerotized from the base to middle region (
Fig. 14
).
